			<header class=3D"entry-header">
				<h1 class=3D"entry-title" itemprop=3D"headline">Cohen=E2=80=99s kappa f=
ree calculator</h1>			</header>

		=09
		<div class=3D"entry-content" itemprop=3D"text">
			<p>If you already know the meaning of the Cohen=E2=80=99s kappa and how =
to interpret it, <a href=3D"https://meta-analysis.actilab.onl/cohen-kappa-f=
ree-calculator/#calculator">go directly to the calculator</a>.</p>
<h2>What is Cohen=E2=80=99s kappa?</h2>
<p>The Cohen=E2=80=99s kappa is a statistical coefficient that represents t=
he degree of accuracy and reliability in a statistical classification. It m=
easures the agreement between two raters (judges) who each classify items i=
nto mutually exclusive categories.<br>
This statistic was introduced by Jacob Cohen in the journal Educational and=
 Psychological Measurement in 1960.<br>
<img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://meta-analysis.actilab.onl/wp-content=
/uploads/2016/05/cohen_kappa_formula.png" alt=3D"Cohen's kappa formula" wid=
th=3D"150" height=3D"90" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp-image-648"><br>
where p<sub>o</sub> is the relative observed agreement among raters, and p<=
sub>e</sub> is the hypothetical probability of chance agreement.</p>
<p>The calculation of the kappa is useful also in meta-analysis during the =
selection of primary studies. It can be measured in two ways:</p>
<ul>
<li>inter-rater reliability: it is to evaluate the degree of agreement betw=
een the choices made by<br>
two ( or more ) independent judges</li>
<li>intra-rater reliability: It is to evaluate the degree of agreement show=
n by the same<br>
person at a distance of time</li>
</ul>
<h2>Interpret the Cohen=E2=80=99s kappa</h2>
<p>To interprete your Cohen=E2=80=99s kappa results you can refer to the fo=
llowing guidelines (see Landis, JR &amp; Koch, GG (1977). The measurement o=
f observer agreement for categorical data. Biometrics, 33, 159-174):</p>
<ul>
<li>0.01 =E2=80=93 0.20 slight agreement</li>
<li>0.21 =E2=80=93 0.40 fair agreement</li>
<li>0.41 =E2=80=93 0.60 moderate agreement</li>
<li>0.61 =E2=80=93 0.80 substantial agreement</li>
<li>0.81 =E2=80=93 1.00 almost perfect or perfect agreement</li>
</ul>
<p>kappa is always less than or equal to 1. A value of 1 implies perfect ag=
reement and values less than 1 imply less than perfect agreement.</p>
<p>It=E2=80=99s possible that kappa is negative. This means that the two ob=
servers agreed less than would be expected just by chance.</p>
<h2 id=3D"calculator">Use the free Cohen=E2=80=99s kappa calculator</h2>
<p>With this tool you can easily calculate the degree of agreement between =
two judges during the selection of the studies to be included in a meta-ana=
lysis.<br>
Complete the fields to obtain the raw percentage of agreement and the value=
 of Cohen=E2=80=99s kappa.</p>
<div id=3D"calcolobox">
<form id=3D"formkappa" action=3D"https://meta-analysis.actilab.onl/cohen-ka=
ppa-free-calculator/#" method=3D"post">
<h3><br class=3D"clear">Please enter number of studies that:</h3>
<p>Both judges agree to include<br>
<input id=3D"entrambiok" max=3D"10000" min=3D"0" name=3D"entrambiok" requir=
ed=3D"" step=3D"1" type=3D"number" value=3D"0"><br>
Both judges agree to exclude<br>
<input id=3D"entrambino" max=3D"10000" min=3D"0" name=3D"entrambino" requir=
ed=3D"" step=3D"1" type=3D"number" value=3D"0"><br>
Only the first judge wants to include<br>
<input id=3D"primook" max=3D"10000" min=3D"0" name=3D"primook" required=3D"=
" step=3D"1" type=3D"number" value=3D"0"><br>
Only the second judge wants to include<br>
<input id=3D"secondook" max=3D"10000" min=3D"0" name=3D"secondook" required=
=3D"" step=3D"1" type=3D"number" value=3D"0"></p>
<p><input type=3D"submit" value=3D"Compute"></p>
</form>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id=3D"risultati">
<h3>Results</h3>
<p>% of agreement: <span id=3D"percaccordo">NaN</span>%</p>
